26 other governmental agencies, and with universities, colleges, junior colleges,
27 community colleges and other institutions concerning the development of
28 Code-enforcement training schools and programs or courses of instruction.
29 (5) Establish minimum standards and levels of education or equivalent experience
30 for all Code-enforcement instructors, teachers or professors.
31 (6) Conduct and encourage research by public and private agencies that shall be
32 designed to improve education and training in the administration of Code
33 enforcement.
34 (7) Adopt and amend bylaws, consistent with law, for its internal management
35 and control; appoint advisory committees as necessary; and enter into
36 contracts and do other things as necessary and incidental to the exercise of its
37 authority pursuant to this Article.
38 (8) Make recommendations concerning any matters within its purview pursuant
39 to this Article.
40 (9) Establish within the Office of the State Fire Marshal a marketplace pool of
41 qualified certified Code-enforcement officials available for the following
42 purposes:
