6 "§ 143-151.13. Required standards and certificates for Code-enforcement
7 officials.certificates.
8 (a) No person shall engage in Code enforcement under this Article unless that person
9 possesses one of the following types of certificates, currently valid, issued by the Board attesting
10 to that person's qualifications to engage in Code enforcement: (i) a standard certificate; (ii) a
11 limited certificate provided for in subsection (c) of this section; or (iii) a probationary certificate
12 provided for in subsection (d) of this section. To obtain a standard certificate, a person must pass
13 an examination, as prescribed by the Board or by a contracting party under G.S. 143-151.16(d),
14 that is based on the North Carolina State Building Code and administrative procedures required
15 for Code enforcement. The Board may issue a standard certificate of qualification to each person
16 who successfully completes the examination. The certificate authorizes that person to engage in
17 the practice of Code enforcement and to practice as a qualified Code-enforcement official in
18 North Carolina. The certificate of qualification shall bear the signatures of the chairman chair
19 and secretary of the Board.
20 (b) The Board shall issue one or more standard certificates to each person seeking to
21 practice Code enforcement as a certified Code-enforcement official by demonstrating the
22 qualifications set forth in subsection (b1) (b2) of this section. Standard certificates are available
23 for each of the following types of qualified for Code-enforcement officials:
24 (1) Building inspector.
25 (2) Electrical inspector.
26 (3) Mechanical inspector.
27 (4) Plumbing inspector.
28 (5) Fire inspector.
29 (6) Residential changeout inspector.
30 (b1) The Board shall issue a standard certificate to each person seeking to practice Code
31 enforcement as a residential changeout special inspector by demonstrating the qualifications set
32 forth in subsection (b2) of this section.
33 (b1)(b2) The holder of a standard certificate may practice Code enforcement only within
34 the inspection area and level described upon the certificate issued by the Board. A
35 Code-enforcement official holder of a standard certificate may qualify and hold one or more
36 certificates. These certificates may be for different levels in different types of positions as defined
37 in this section and in rules adopted by the Board.
38 (b2)(b3) A Code-enforcement official holding a certificate indicating a specified level of
39 proficiency in a particular type of position may hold a position calling for that type of
40 qualification anywhere in the State. With respect to all types of Code-enforcement officials, those
41 with Level I, Level II, or Level III certificates shall be qualified to inspect and approve only those
42 types and sizes of buildings as specified in rules adopted by the Board.
43 (c) A Code-enforcement official holding office as of the date specified in this subsection
44 for the county or municipality by which he is employed, shall not be required to possess a
