9 "§ 143-151.17. Grounds for disciplinary actions; investigation; administrative procedures.
10 (a) The Board has the power to suspend, revoke, demote to a lower level, or refuse to
11 grant a certificate issued under this Article to any person to whom any of the following applies:
12 (1) Has been convicted of a felony against this State or the United States, or
13 convicted of a felony in another state that would also be a felony if it had been
14 committed in this State.
15 (2) Has obtained certification through fraud, deceit, or perjury.
16 (3) Has knowingly aided or abetted any person practicing contrary to the
17 provisions of this Article or the North Carolina State Building Code or any
18 building codes adopted by a federally recognized Indian Tribe.
19 (4) Has defrauded the public or attempted to do so.
20 (5) Has affixed his or her a signature to a report of inspection or other instrument
21 of service if no inspection has been made by him or her or under his or her
22 immediate and responsible direction.made.
23 (6) Has been guilty of willful misconduct, gross negligence, or gross
24 incompetence.
25 (b) The Board may investigate the actions of any qualified Code-enforcement official
26 certificate holder or applicant upon the verified complaint in writing of any person alleging a
27 violation of subsection (a) of this section. The Board may suspend, revoke, or demote to a lower
28 level any certificate of any qualified Code-enforcement official certificate holder and refuse to
29 grant a certificate to any applicant, whom it finds to have been guilty of one or more of the actions
30 set out in subsection (a) of this section as grounds for disciplinary action.
31 (c) A denial, suspension, revocation, or demotion to a lower level of a certificate issued
32 under this Article shall be made in accordance with Chapter 150B of the General Statutes.
33 (d) The Board may deny an application for a certificate for any of the grounds that are
34 described in subsection (a) of this section. Within 30 days after receipt of a notification that an
35 application for a certificate has been denied, the applicant may make a written request for a
36 review by a committee designated by the chairman chair of the Board to determine the
37 reasonableness of the Board's action. The review shall be completed without undue delay, and
38 the applicant shall be notified promptly in writing as to the outcome of the review. Within 30
39 days after service of the notification as to the outcome, the applicant may make a written request
40 for a hearing under Article 3A of Chapter 150B of the General Statutes if the applicant disagrees
41 with the outcome.
42 (e) This section applies to Code-enforcement officials and applicants who are employed
43 or seek to be employed by a federally recognized Indian Tribe to perform inspections on tribal
44 lands.
