1 changeout special inspector certificate. To obtain a certificate, a person must pass an
2 examination, as prescribed by the Board, that is based on the North Carolina State Building Code,
3 administrative procedures applicable to permit administration, and relevant topics related to the
4 inspection of residential changeout work as described in G.S. 160D-1106.1. The Board may issue
5 a certificate to each person who successfully applies and completes the examination. The
6 certificate shall bear the signatures of the chair and secretary of the Board.
7 (b) Professional Development Standards for Renewal. – The Board may establish
8 professional development requirements for residential changeout special inspector certificate as
9 a condition of the renewal of their certificates. The purpose of these professional development
10 requirements is to assist in maintaining professional competence. A certificate holder subject to
11 this section shall present evidence to the Board at each certificate renewal after initial certification
12 that during the 12 months before the certificate expiration date, the certificate holder has
13 completed the required number of credit hours in courses approved by the Board. Annual
14 continuing education hour requirements shall be determined by the Board. The Board may, for
15 good cause shown, grant extensions of time to certificate holders to comply with these
16 requirements.
17 (c) Renewal Application. – A residential changeout special inspector certificate must be
18 renewed annually on or before the first day of July.
19 (d) Fee Authorization. – The Board shall establish a schedule of fees to be paid by each
20 applicant for initial certification and renewal certification as a residential changeout special
21 inspector. A fee of not more than twenty dollars ($20.00), as determined by the Board, must be
22 paid by any applicant to the Board for the issuance of an initial certification. A fee of not more
23 than ten dollars ($10.00), as determined by the Board, must be paid by any applicant to the Board
24 for the issuance of a renewal certification. The Board is authorized to charge an extra four dollar
25 ($4.00) late renewal fee for renewal applications made after the first day of July each year.
26 (e) Code-Enforcement Official Exam Waiver. – The Board shall, without requiring an
27 examination, grant a certificate pursuant to this section to any person who, at the time of
28 application, possesses a Building Inspector standard certificate issued by the Board and who is
29 in good standing. The Board may assess a fee for a certificate issued pursuant to this subsection
30 to the extent authorized by subsection (d) of this section for an initial certification.
31 (f) Certification of Licensed Contractors. – The Board shall issue a standard certificate
32 to any person who is currently licensed to practice as a plumbing or heating contractor, licensed
33 pursuant to Article 2 of Chapter 87 of the General Statutes, provided the person successfully
34 completes a short course, as prescribed by the Board, relating to the North Carolina State
35 Building Code and Code enforcement administration.
36 (g) Comity. – The Board may, without requiring an examination, grant a certificate
37 pursuant to this section to any person who, at the time of application, is a similarly certified
38 Building Inspector in good standing by a similar board of another jurisdiction where standards
39 are acceptable to the Board. The certificate granted under this subsection shall expire after one
40 year unless, within that time period, the holder completes a short course, as prescribed by the
41 Board, based on the North Carolina State Building Code and administrative procedures described
42 in subsection (a) of this section. The Board may assess a fee for a certificate issued pursuant to
43 this subsection, to the extent authorized by subsection (d) of this section for an initial
44 certification."
45 SECTION 4.1.(b) Article 11 of Chapter 160D of the General Statutes is amended
46 by adding a new section to read:
47 "§ 160D-1106.1. Alternate inspection method by residential changeout special inspectors.
48 (a) Notwithstanding the building inspection requirements of this Article, a local
49 government shall accept and approve, without further responsibility to inspect, a residential
50 changeout inspected by a residential changeout special inspector if all of the following conditions
51 are met:
DRH10259-BGf-2 Page 27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The residential changeout is completed by a contractor licensed pursuant to
2 Article 2 of Chapter 87 of the General Statutes, who is different than the
3 residential changeout special inspector charged with inspection of that
4 residential changeout.
5 (2) The new appliance, and related connections, subject to the residential
6 changeout meets all of the following conditions:
7 a. The new appliance requires no alterations to the existing ducting, fuel
8 type, or piping systems other than what is required for transitioning to
9 the new appliance.
10 b. Any venting associated with the new appliance shall be allowed to be
11 installed, replaced, and repaired where such venting does not pass
12 through a rated assembly.
13 c. Any new gas appliance shall be of the same category as the appliance
14 being replaced, if applicable.
15 d. The new appliance does not require relocation, excluding minor
16 adjustments in the same general vicinity.
17 e. The installation of the new appliance does not require the relocation
18 or addition to the existing electrical system, except the replacement of
19 the appliance's branch circuit overcurrent device, or the replacement
20 of the appliance's branch circuit where such circuit does not pass
21 through a rated assembly shall be allowed.
22 f. The electrical branch circuit serving the appliance is single phase.
23 (3) Field inspection of the installation is performed by a residential changeout
24 special inspector, certified pursuant to Article 9C of Chapter 143 of the
25 General Statutes.
26 (4) The residential changeout special inspector provides the local government
27 with a signed written certification that work outlined within subdivisions (1)
28 and (2) of this subsection have been met and is compliant with the North
29 Carolina State Building Code. The certification required under this
30 subdivision shall be provided by electronic or physical delivery, and its receipt
31 shall be promptly acknowledged by the local government through reciprocal
32 means. The certification shall be made on forms created by the Office of the
33 State Fire Marshal, in consultation with the North Carolina Residential Code
34 Council, which shall include the following information:
35 a. Permit number.
36 b. Date of inspection.
37 c. Type of inspection.
38 d. Contractor's name and license number.
39 e. Street address of the job location.
40 f. Name, address, telephone number, and certificate number of the
41 person responsible for the residential changeout special inspection.
42 (b) In accepting certifications of inspections under subsection (a) of this section, a local
43 government shall not require information other than what is required within the certification
44 required under subsection (a) of this section.
45 (c) Upon the acceptance and approval of a signed certification by the local government
46 as required under subsection (a) of this section, notwithstanding the issuance of a certificate of
47 compliance, the local government, its inspection department, and its inspectors are discharged
48 and released from any liabilities, duties, and responsibilities imposed by this Article with respect
49 to or in common law from any claim arising out of or attributed to the residential changeout
50 inspection for which the signed written certification was submitted.
